1
00:00:05,380 --> 00:00:07,424
I'm so nervous. Will I do a good job?

2
00:00:08,383 --> 00:00:09,384
Gosh.

3
00:00:09,468 --> 00:00:10,511
HOCRATES SEEMS NERVOUS

4
00:00:10,594 --> 00:00:12,262
I haven't met today's customer before.

5
00:00:14,139 --> 00:00:17,226
SIXTH BOOK: <i>READING THE MOVES OF LIFE</i>

6
00:00:18,560 --> 00:00:20,687
He should be arriving any time now.

7
00:00:21,855 --> 00:00:22,940
Why am I so nervous?

8
00:00:24,316 --> 00:00:25,484
Hello.

9
00:00:25,901 --> 00:00:26,944
- Excuse me.
- Goodness.

10
00:00:27,027 --> 00:00:29,571
Could I buy a book?

11
00:00:30,239 --> 00:00:31,323
Did you make a reservation?

12
00:00:31,406 --> 00:00:34,034
LEE SE-DOL, FORMER GO PLAYER, PROFESSOR
Yes, I think so.

13
00:00:34,117 --> 00:00:36,286
- Right. Nice to meet you.
- Nice to meet you.

14
00:00:36,370 --> 00:00:37,579
Please, have a seat.

15
00:00:37,663 --> 00:00:39,581
So this is what it's like.

16
00:00:41,208 --> 00:00:44,378
This is a space where people
are read like books, Hodong's Bookshop,

17
00:00:44,461 --> 00:00:47,589
located in the most beautiful neighborhood
in the world,

18
00:00:47,673 --> 00:00:48,924
Kangho-dong.

19
00:00:49,007 --> 00:00:51,343
- Welcome.
- Thank you for having me.

20
00:00:51,426 --> 00:00:56,098
Most of our guests
have wanted to sell books.

21
00:00:56,223 --> 00:00:58,725
You're the first one who wants to buy one.

22
00:00:58,809 --> 00:01:03,063
I wanted to buy a book
recommended by you, Hocrates.

23
00:01:03,146 --> 00:01:04,231
- I see.
- Yes.

24
00:01:04,398 --> 00:01:07,150
It's different from what I expected,
now that we met in person.

25
00:01:07,317 --> 00:01:10,028
My face is way bigger
than what you expected, right?

26
00:01:10,362 --> 00:01:11,572
GLANCING
Not at all.

27
00:01:11,655 --> 00:01:12,614
- Are you sure?
- Yes.

28
00:01:12,698 --> 00:01:15,158
Actually, I used to have
better proportions in the past.

29
00:01:15,242 --> 00:01:16,118
I used to be bigger.

30
00:01:16,201 --> 00:01:17,244
TAKING A LOOK
But I started losing weight

31
00:01:17,411 --> 00:01:19,037
everywhere except in my face.

32
00:01:19,121 --> 00:01:20,080
That's right.

33
00:01:20,372 --> 00:01:21,331
I mean...

34
00:01:21,415 --> 00:01:22,541
HE BLURT OUT HIS TRUE FEELINGS

35
00:01:22,624 --> 00:01:24,710
No, I meant...

36
00:01:24,918 --> 00:01:29,298
Your head must've gotten big
from all that knowledge and wisdom.

37
00:01:29,923 --> 00:01:31,842
TRYING TO MAKE UP FOR HIS MISTAKE
That must be why.

38
00:01:31,967 --> 00:01:34,428
Right. By the way, you're also famous

39
00:01:34,511 --> 00:01:37,055
for that special tone of voice,
aren't you?

40
00:01:37,139 --> 00:01:40,017
- It's so exciting and cool
- Right.

41
00:01:40,100 --> 00:01:41,768
hearing it in person.

42
00:01:41,852 --> 00:01:43,520
It's very distinctive, right?

43
00:01:46,356 --> 00:01:48,817
You do sound a little nervous.

44
00:01:48,901 --> 00:01:49,985
I suppose.

45
00:01:50,068 --> 00:01:52,696
Would you like me to give you a hug
to make you feel better?

46
00:01:52,779 --> 00:01:54,323
No, that'll make me more nervous.

47
00:01:55,532 --> 00:01:58,243
HOCRATES RESOLVES AWKWARDNESS THROUGH HUGS

48
00:01:58,744 --> 00:02:00,370
I guess it might work.

49
00:02:00,454 --> 00:02:01,830
- Let me give you a hug.
- Okay.

50
00:02:01,914 --> 00:02:03,081
RELUCTANTLY AGREEING TO A HUG

51
00:02:03,165 --> 00:02:05,584
- How should I...
- Let me just grab you like this.

52
00:02:05,667 --> 00:02:07,127
IS THIS A HUG?
What are you going to do?

53
00:02:07,211 --> 00:02:09,338
I wanted to hug you like this.

54
00:02:09,463 --> 00:02:11,006
- I did this a lot in the past.
- I see.

55
00:02:11,089 --> 00:02:13,258
LIFTING HIM AS IF HE WEIGHS NOTHING
This feels nostalgic. Before...

56
00:02:13,342 --> 00:02:14,426
GENTLY PUTTING HIM DOWN
Okay.

57
00:02:14,927 --> 00:02:16,845
THE CUSTOMER IS NO LONGER NERVOUS

58
00:02:16,929 --> 00:02:18,055
I once hosted

59
00:02:18,138 --> 00:02:20,474
- a TV show called <i>The Knee-Drop Guru.</i>
- Right.

60
00:02:20,557 --> 00:02:22,559
- I lifted my guests all the time.
- I remember.

61
00:02:22,643 --> 00:02:24,394
- I would've done this if we met then.
- I see.

62
00:02:24,478 --> 00:02:27,356
It felt like there was no gravity
for a moment.

63
00:02:28,106 --> 00:02:30,442
SUDDENLY EXPERIENCING ZERO GRAVITY
IN A BOOKSHOP

64
00:02:30,526 --> 00:02:33,237
- I've been lifted a few times before,
- Right.

65
00:02:33,320 --> 00:02:35,656
IT'S NOT A COMMON EXPERIENCE THOUGH
but none of them felt like this.

66
00:02:36,949 --> 00:02:38,534
CUSTOMER SATISFACTION: 5/5

67
00:02:38,742 --> 00:02:41,036
As you can see here,

68
00:02:41,119 --> 00:02:42,663
we don't accept cash or credit cards here.

69
00:02:42,746 --> 00:02:45,707
- We only accept stories.
- I see.

70
00:02:45,791 --> 00:02:48,126
That's the price for the books.
And I also make book recommendations.

71
00:02:48,210 --> 00:02:50,754
I only have cash and credit cards, though.

72
00:02:51,630 --> 00:02:53,549
WHY DIDN'T ANYONE POINT THIS OUT BEFORE?

73
00:02:53,632 --> 00:02:55,175
Let me listen to your story,

74
00:02:55,259 --> 00:02:58,303
and I'll recommend a book
that you might like.

75
00:02:58,387 --> 00:03:00,347
Let's get started, then.

76
00:03:00,430 --> 00:03:01,849
Yes, all right.

77
00:03:01,932 --> 00:03:03,934
- Your name is Lee Se-dol, right?
- Yes.

78
00:03:04,017 --> 00:03:05,435
Do you have any siblings?

79
00:03:05,519 --> 00:03:07,062
I have two older brothers
and two older sisters.

80
00:03:07,145 --> 00:03:08,397
- You're the youngest out of five?
- Yes.

81
00:03:08,480 --> 00:03:10,190
I'm also the third son.

82
00:03:10,274 --> 00:03:11,900
So the <i>"se"</i> in your name means "three"?

83
00:03:11,984 --> 00:03:13,735
- Yes.
- Then is the second son named...

84
00:03:14,278 --> 00:03:15,571
- Du-dol?
- "Cha-dol," because<i> "cha" </i>means "next."

85
00:03:15,654 --> 00:03:16,655
"Cha-dol"?

86
00:03:17,573 --> 00:03:18,907
IT REMINDS HOCRATES OF
<i>CHADOLBAGI</i>, BEEF BRISKET POINT

87
00:03:18,991 --> 00:03:21,743
- That's how your parents named you guys?
- Yes.

88
00:03:21,827 --> 00:03:25,581
THIRD SON, LEE SE-DOL
SECOND SON, LEE CHA-DOL

89
00:03:25,664 --> 00:03:28,333
You put your job down
as "board game designer."

90
00:03:28,417 --> 00:03:29,960
A BOARD GAME DESIGNER?

91
00:03:30,169 --> 00:03:32,546
I'm not sure
what my actual "job" is right now.

92
00:03:32,629 --> 00:03:35,174
I mean, I really did design board games.

93
00:03:35,299 --> 00:03:38,468
- And I'm also a collaborating professor
- Yes?

94
00:03:38,552 --> 00:03:40,804
at Ulsan National Institute
of Science and Technology.

95
00:03:40,888 --> 00:03:43,849
- I also make TV appearances sometimes.
- Right.

96
00:03:43,932 --> 00:03:47,519
So you're a Go player, a professor,
a game designer, and a TV personality.

97
00:03:48,187 --> 00:03:49,646
- Yes.
- You have a lot of jobs.

98
00:03:49,897 --> 00:03:51,773
If you could pick one, what would it be?

99
00:03:51,857 --> 00:03:54,193
I think I'm in the process

100
00:03:54,568 --> 00:03:57,154
of creating a new job
for myself, actually.

101
00:03:57,237 --> 00:04:00,657
After I retired as a Go player,
I've been looking for something

102
00:04:00,741 --> 00:04:02,743
that I can be as passionate about
as I was about Go.

103
00:04:02,826 --> 00:04:04,119
So you're a job seeker.

104
00:04:06,955 --> 00:04:08,582
I never thought of it like that!

105
00:04:08,957 --> 00:04:10,167
THE WISDOM OF A 2,000-YEAR-OLD

106
00:04:10,250 --> 00:04:11,585
So that's what I am.

107
00:04:11,668 --> 00:04:13,921
- In short.
- Yes, exactly.

108
00:04:14,004 --> 00:04:15,255
You're a writer too, aren't you?

109
00:04:15,422 --> 00:04:17,382
- Let me just grab something.
- Okay.

110
00:04:17,466 --> 00:04:19,468
Hold on. Where is it?

111
00:04:19,927 --> 00:04:21,887
Where's that book?
I know we have it somewhere.

112
00:04:22,137 --> 00:04:23,972
Oh, here it is.

113
00:04:25,390 --> 00:04:28,477
<i>- Lee Se-dol, Reading the Moves of Life.</i>
- Yes.

114
00:04:29,144 --> 00:04:30,729
- This is...
- I'm embarrassed.

115
00:04:30,812 --> 00:04:32,189
<i>LEE SE-DOL, READING THE MOVES OF LIFE</i>
BY LEE SE-DOL

116
00:04:32,272 --> 00:04:34,233
ESSAY ABOUT MAKING CHOICES AND DECISIONS
THROUGH WINS AND EXPERIENCES

117
00:04:34,316 --> 00:04:36,151
- Professor, while I was reading it,
- Yes?

118
00:04:36,235 --> 00:04:38,403
- I marked down some questions.
- I see.

119
00:04:38,487 --> 00:04:39,780
I read it very closely.

120
00:04:39,863 --> 00:04:41,490
IT'S LIKE AN AUTHOR MEET AND GREET

121
00:04:41,573 --> 00:04:42,574
I was so moved.

122
00:04:42,908 --> 00:04:44,952
GIVING AN ORAL BOOK REPORT
You went through so many struggles,

123
00:04:45,035 --> 00:04:47,246
FEELING BASHFUL
but you wrote about them so honestly.

124
00:04:47,329 --> 00:04:48,372
It comforted me.

125
00:04:49,373 --> 00:04:51,250
The part about your family
was especially moving.

126
00:04:52,042 --> 00:04:53,252
Thank you so much.

127
00:04:53,752 --> 00:04:55,504
What made you write this book?

128
00:04:56,046 --> 00:05:00,676
I wanted to tell an honest story
about both my personal life

129
00:05:01,009 --> 00:05:02,928
and my professional life.

130
00:05:03,011 --> 00:05:05,681
You said the game of Go was like life.

131
00:05:05,764 --> 00:05:07,808
And after reading this book,

132
00:05:07,891 --> 00:05:10,185
I realized that we use a lot of Go terms

133
00:05:10,269 --> 00:05:12,479
- in our daily lives.
- Exactly.

134
00:05:12,563 --> 00:05:16,984
"Losing move," "incomplete life,"
and "tiger's mouth" are all Go terms.

135
00:05:17,067 --> 00:05:18,944
"Trick play," too.

136
00:05:19,027 --> 00:05:20,028
"Tiger's mouth"?

137
00:05:20,112 --> 00:05:21,864
- That's from Go too?
- Yes.

138
00:05:22,239 --> 00:05:24,366
The Korean word for "pushover" is <i>hogu,</i>

139
00:05:24,491 --> 00:05:26,118
which literally means "tiger's mouth."

140
00:05:26,201 --> 00:05:28,078
Yes. And the "tiger's mouth" formation

141
00:05:28,287 --> 00:05:31,790
is where three enemy stones
surround one stone.

142
00:05:31,874 --> 00:05:33,125
So "walking into a tiger's mouth" means--

143
00:05:33,208 --> 00:05:35,002
That phrase is also from Go?

144
00:05:35,085 --> 00:05:38,839
Yes, it describes a pushover who is
dumb enough to walk into this formation.

145
00:05:38,922 --> 00:05:40,174
- Yes.
- I see.

146
00:05:40,299 --> 00:05:44,845
Then what's your favorite Go term,
Professor?

147
00:05:45,137 --> 00:05:47,139
As for me personally,

148
00:05:47,306 --> 00:05:49,308
- it's "winning move."
- "Winning move"?

149
00:05:50,184 --> 00:05:52,436
As for me...

150
00:05:52,936 --> 00:05:55,147
One of the things I love about Go

151
00:05:55,355 --> 00:05:59,193
is that you can
clearly determine the "losing move."

152
00:05:59,526 --> 00:06:01,778
You know where you went wrong.

153
00:06:01,862 --> 00:06:06,742
But in life, often you can't determine
what the losing move is

154
00:06:06,825 --> 00:06:08,535
when you experience a failure.

155
00:06:08,952 --> 00:06:10,412
"What did I do wrong?"

156
00:06:10,495 --> 00:06:14,291
No matter how hard you think about it,
you can never be sure

157
00:06:14,499 --> 00:06:15,626
what the losing move was.

158
00:06:15,709 --> 00:06:18,295
But that's not the case in the game of Go.

159
00:06:18,378 --> 00:06:21,632
You can tell where you went wrong
and learn from your mistake.

160
00:06:21,715 --> 00:06:24,259
But you always end up
making the same mistake.

161
00:06:25,677 --> 00:06:27,638
KNOWING THE LOSING MOVE
DOESN'T MEAN YOU NEVER DO IT AGAIN

162
00:06:27,721 --> 00:06:29,556
It's comforting to me

163
00:06:29,640 --> 00:06:31,433
that even you aren't always perfect.

164
00:06:31,517 --> 00:06:34,394
Then let's start reading the story

165
00:06:34,478 --> 00:06:37,231
of your life, Se-dol.

166
00:06:37,397 --> 00:06:40,150
First of all, we need to mention
the game of Go.

167
00:06:40,234 --> 00:06:41,985
- Of course.
- How did you start?

168
00:06:42,611 --> 00:06:45,656
I started playing
when I was five years old.

169
00:06:45,739 --> 00:06:47,574
SE-DOL IS SEVEN IN THIS PHOTO

170
00:06:47,658 --> 00:06:50,494
I was born on an island called Bigeumdo
in Sinan County.

171
00:06:50,661 --> 00:06:53,413
<i>- You were born on Bigeumdo?</i>
<i>- Yes.</i>

172
00:06:53,497 --> 00:06:55,749
SE-DOL, OLDER BROTHER
<i>My father really loved the game of Go.</i>

173
00:06:55,832 --> 00:06:57,292
FATHER, OLDEST BROTHER
<i>So besides myself,</i>

174
00:06:57,376 --> 00:06:59,837
my oldest brother
is also a professional Go player

175
00:06:59,920 --> 00:07:01,463
- who's still active.
- I see.

176
00:07:01,547 --> 00:07:05,175
OLDEST BROTHER, OLDER SISTER, SE-DOL
<i>My sisters would carry me to the Go board</i>

177
00:07:05,259 --> 00:07:07,010
<i>and teach me how to play.</i>

178
00:07:07,135 --> 00:07:08,470
<i>That's how I started.</i>

179
00:07:08,554 --> 00:07:10,973
- You're the youngest of five, right?
- Right.

180
00:07:11,056 --> 00:07:13,100
But Go is difficult, isn't it?

181
00:07:13,183 --> 00:07:15,811
At least for a little child.

182
00:07:15,894 --> 00:07:17,229
- For me...
- Yes?

183
00:07:17,437 --> 00:07:20,232
I can't really remember
how I felt when I was five.

184
00:07:20,315 --> 00:07:22,317
- Of course.
- I only have vague memories of that time.

185
00:07:22,568 --> 00:07:24,862
But I can clearly remember
that from six onward,

186
00:07:24,945 --> 00:07:26,446
I won against older boys.

187
00:07:26,530 --> 00:07:28,740
Even though I started later than them,

188
00:07:28,824 --> 00:07:32,160
I beat all the older boys
in the neighborhood.

189
00:07:32,828 --> 00:07:35,831
I had so much fun doing that.

190
00:07:35,914 --> 00:07:37,875
- You mean winning?
- Yes, because at that age,

191
00:07:37,958 --> 00:07:39,668
it's really hard to beat someone

192
00:07:39,918 --> 00:07:41,253
who's even a year older.

193
00:07:41,336 --> 00:07:42,880
- Yes, it's not easy.
- Well...

194
00:07:42,963 --> 00:07:44,882
It isn't easy for a seven-year-old kid

195
00:07:44,965 --> 00:07:46,925
to beat an eight-year-old kid, right?

196
00:07:47,009 --> 00:07:48,427
And if they're older than that,

197
00:07:48,510 --> 00:07:50,387
it's practically impossible,
no matter what game it is.

198
00:07:50,470 --> 00:07:52,389
- At that age, even six months
- Right.

199
00:07:52,472 --> 00:07:54,391
makes an enormous difference.

200
00:07:54,474 --> 00:07:56,226
But I could beat them in Go.

201
00:07:57,394 --> 00:08:00,898
<i>That's why I never found Go</i>
<i>that difficult.</i>

202
00:08:00,981 --> 00:08:03,358
<i>The games were always fun for me.</i>

203
00:08:04,276 --> 00:08:05,986
When I started elementary school,

204
00:08:06,820 --> 00:08:09,948
I started thinking about
and studying the moves on my own.

205
00:08:10,199 --> 00:08:12,951
STARTED STUDYING ON HIS OWN AT AGE SEVEN
<i>That's how I trained myself.</i>

206
00:08:13,035 --> 00:08:15,746
I couldn't have done that
if I hadn't loved it.

207
00:08:15,829 --> 00:08:16,830
- That's right.
- Yes.

208
00:08:16,914 --> 00:08:18,457
Did your father encourage it?

209
00:08:18,540 --> 00:08:20,584
So when I started elementary school,

210
00:08:20,667 --> 00:08:23,795
<i>I played against my father a lot.</i>

211
00:08:24,546 --> 00:08:27,174
At first, I lost most of the games.

212
00:08:27,257 --> 00:08:29,510
- My father was better.
- Of course.

213
00:08:29,593 --> 00:08:31,845
But from May or June,
we were almost at the same level.

214
00:08:33,096 --> 00:08:35,641
I won half of our games,
and he won the other half.

215
00:08:35,724 --> 00:08:37,768
- When you were in first grade?
- Yes.

216
00:08:37,935 --> 00:08:40,229
And in the third quarter...

217
00:08:40,771 --> 00:08:41,772
You got better than him?

218
00:08:42,189 --> 00:08:43,232
He stopped playing with me.

219
00:08:43,315 --> 00:08:45,901
- He was intimidated by you.
- He stopped playing with me after that.

220
00:08:46,318 --> 00:08:47,903
When we were about the same level,

221
00:08:47,986 --> 00:08:50,072
he used to say he lost
because he'd had a drink

222
00:08:50,155 --> 00:08:51,949
or because he was tired.

223
00:08:52,366 --> 00:08:53,951
SE-DOL'S FATHER WAS IN DENIAL

224
00:08:54,034 --> 00:08:55,869
Did he tell you he simply got careless

225
00:08:55,953 --> 00:08:58,497
- or that he'd had a drink?
- Yes.

226
00:08:58,580 --> 00:09:00,123
He was making excuses?

227
00:09:00,207 --> 00:09:01,959
Another thing I remember

228
00:09:02,042 --> 00:09:04,670
is that he often sent me on errands
to buy rice wine.

229
00:09:05,379 --> 00:09:07,005
And there's a small hole in the bottle

230
00:09:07,089 --> 00:09:08,715
that you can drink from.

231
00:09:09,341 --> 00:09:10,509
- Seriously?
- Yes.

232
00:09:10,843 --> 00:09:12,594
Those tiny drops tasted so good.

233
00:09:12,970 --> 00:09:13,929
So sweet.

234
00:09:15,138 --> 00:09:17,558
- It must've been a tiny amount, right?
- And I remember--

235
00:09:17,641 --> 00:09:19,685
- You were just curious.
- Yes, exactly.

236
00:09:19,768 --> 00:09:21,395
I remember thinking, "I drank too."

237
00:09:21,478 --> 00:09:22,980
I DRANK SOME OF WHAT DAD DRANK TOO

238
00:09:23,939 --> 00:09:25,607
PROVING DAD'S ARGUMENT WRONG

239
00:09:26,400 --> 00:09:29,945
Were you especially talented
even among your siblings?

240
00:09:30,070 --> 00:09:31,238
I remember

241
00:09:31,321 --> 00:09:32,990
my father told me when I was six

242
00:09:33,574 --> 00:09:35,784
that I'd be playing this professionally.

243
00:09:36,493 --> 00:09:38,203
- Not as a hobby?
- No.

244
00:09:38,370 --> 00:09:40,455
At the time, I didn't know what he meant.

245
00:09:40,539 --> 00:09:41,748
I didn't understand.

246
00:09:41,832 --> 00:09:43,834
What six-year-old kid would?

247
00:09:43,959 --> 00:09:47,045
But I still clearly remember
his face and his voice

248
00:09:47,129 --> 00:09:48,922
when he told me that.

249
00:09:49,423 --> 00:09:50,674
HE ALREADY RECOGNIZED
6-YEAR-OLD SE-DOL'S TALENT

250
00:09:50,757 --> 00:09:53,135
<i>Yes, I remember it very clearly.</i>

251
00:09:53,510 --> 00:09:54,344
Why did he say that?

252
00:09:54,428 --> 00:09:56,138
Was it because he kept losing to you

253
00:09:56,221 --> 00:09:58,015
even though he tried his best to win?

254
00:09:58,098 --> 00:10:00,767
That was in 1989.

255
00:10:00,976 --> 00:10:03,520
That year, Master Cho Hun-hyun

256
00:10:04,188 --> 00:10:06,440
won the Ing Cup,
an international Go tournament.

257
00:10:06,523 --> 00:10:07,566
Right, the Ing Cup.

258
00:10:07,649 --> 00:10:08,525
INTERNATIONAL GO TOURNAMENT
HELD ONCE EVERY 4 YEARS

259
00:10:08,859 --> 00:10:10,819
My father and I

260
00:10:11,236 --> 00:10:13,739
were watching it together on television,

261
00:10:14,281 --> 00:10:18,785
and he told me I'd go professional
after he saw Master Cho win the Ing Cup.

262
00:10:19,411 --> 00:10:22,706
I guess he realized
being a professional Go player

263
00:10:23,123 --> 00:10:25,959
was a viable career option for me then.

264
00:10:27,002 --> 00:10:29,588
A NATIONAL PASTIME IN KOREA
IN THE 80S AND 90S

265
00:10:29,671 --> 00:10:32,132
THE GAME OF GO

266
00:10:32,591 --> 00:10:34,176
BACK THEN, THERE WERE ONLY AROUND

267
00:10:34,259 --> 00:10:35,552
100 PRO GO PLAYERS

268
00:10:36,094 --> 00:10:38,680
AND LESS THAN 10 PLAYERS WHO WERE 9-DAN

269
00:10:38,764 --> 00:10:41,767
IN 1989,
A BOWL OF BLACK BEAN NOODLES COST 800 WON

270
00:10:42,184 --> 00:10:43,936
MEANWHILE, MASTER CHO HUN-HYUN

271
00:10:44,019 --> 00:10:46,313
BECAME THE FIRST TO WIN
AN INTERNATIONAL TOURNAMENT

272
00:10:46,772 --> 00:10:49,274
AND EARNED MORE THAN
100 MILLION WON A YEAR

273
00:10:49,358 --> 00:10:50,734
THAT WAS THE BEGINNING

274
00:10:50,817 --> 00:10:53,278
OF THE GOLDEN AGE OF KOREAN GO

275
00:10:53,612 --> 00:10:55,113
When did you debut as a pro player?

276
00:10:55,197 --> 00:10:56,448
When I was 12 years old.

277
00:10:56,532 --> 00:11:00,160
I was in sixth grade.

278
00:11:00,827 --> 00:11:03,747
To be honest,
before I became a professional,

279
00:11:03,997 --> 00:11:05,165
I really thought I was the best.

280
00:11:06,291 --> 00:11:08,836
I never doubted that I was good enough

281
00:11:08,919 --> 00:11:10,504
to go pro, you know?

282
00:11:10,712 --> 00:11:12,965
So even when I began preparations
to go pro,

283
00:11:13,048 --> 00:11:14,883
I wasn't worried about it at all.

284
00:11:16,009 --> 00:11:17,761
Do you really remember everything?

285
00:11:17,928 --> 00:11:19,888
At the time, going pro was a big deal

286
00:11:19,972 --> 00:11:22,432
for everyone in the family.

287
00:11:23,392 --> 00:11:25,727
But even as a kid,
I was like, "It's done. I'm in."

288
00:11:25,811 --> 00:11:26,687
NO BIG DEAL

289
00:11:27,187 --> 00:11:29,857
HE MUST BE PROUD
OF HIS CONFIDENT PAST SELF

290
00:11:29,940 --> 00:11:31,149
"Don't worry about it."

291
00:11:33,151 --> 00:11:36,280
But I honestly didn't think it was
something to make a big deal out of.

292
00:11:36,363 --> 00:11:37,865
- You weren't excited, even a littlebit?
- I wasn't.

293
00:11:38,073 --> 00:11:39,783
I thought,
"I should've done this last year."

294
00:11:40,742 --> 00:11:42,244
"Sorry I'm late."

295
00:11:42,786 --> 00:11:44,037
HE WAS CHEEKY

296
00:11:44,329 --> 00:11:47,624
I was so confident back then.

297
00:11:48,041 --> 00:11:50,002
I thought I was the best.

298
00:11:50,085 --> 00:11:54,047
Even the players who were two years older
were no match for me.

299
00:11:54,131 --> 00:11:56,425
<i>- You were just that good.</i>
<i>- I was.</i>

300
00:11:56,884 --> 00:12:00,053
Didn't you have a hard time
adjusting to Seoul

301
00:12:00,137 --> 00:12:02,222
when you moved there
to become a professional?

302
00:12:02,306 --> 00:12:03,682
I loved it, actually.

303
00:12:04,308 --> 00:12:07,060
- It's not that I didn't miss my parents,
- Right.

304
00:12:07,269 --> 00:12:11,523
but the house I was in...

305
00:12:11,607 --> 00:12:14,776
<i>So I moved in with my teacher,</i>
<i>Master Kwon Gap-yong.</i>

306
00:12:14,860 --> 00:12:17,446
<i>He housed me and fed me.</i>

307
00:12:17,529 --> 00:12:19,031
<i>- I see.</i>
<i>- That was common practice.</i>

308
00:12:19,573 --> 00:12:21,658
I was the youngest disciple he had.

309
00:12:21,742 --> 00:12:22,659
HEHE
THE YOUNGEST DISCIPLE

310
00:12:22,743 --> 00:12:26,663
- There were five disciples, including me,
- I see.

311
00:12:26,830 --> 00:12:28,707
and since they were all older,

312
00:12:28,790 --> 00:12:30,209
they took care of and looked after me.

313
00:12:30,626 --> 00:12:34,004
So did Master Kwon and his wife.

314
00:12:34,171 --> 00:12:35,881
It was a perk of being the youngest.

315
00:12:35,964 --> 00:12:39,885
But once you go pro, and I don't know
if this is a good thing or not...

316
00:12:40,135 --> 00:12:41,678
No one teaches you anything anymore.

317
00:12:42,137 --> 00:12:43,263
You have to fend for yourself.

318
00:12:43,555 --> 00:12:44,640
Not even Master Kwon?

319
00:12:45,516 --> 00:12:46,600
No, not even him.

320
00:12:47,976 --> 00:12:51,522
Of course,
since I was only in sixth grade,

321
00:12:51,813 --> 00:12:54,358
he still taught me
other things about life,

322
00:12:54,441 --> 00:12:55,734
but nothing about Go.

323
00:12:56,276 --> 00:12:58,195
Until I went pro,

324
00:12:58,278 --> 00:13:00,572
I had all these teachers

325
00:13:00,697 --> 00:13:03,951
advising me and giving me lessons,

326
00:13:04,034 --> 00:13:06,203
but as soon as I turned pro,
I was left alone.

327
00:13:06,453 --> 00:13:09,706
They had other disciples to teach now.

328
00:13:09,790 --> 00:13:11,124
They were respecting me as a professional.

329
00:13:12,626 --> 00:13:14,044
But you were only 12.

330
00:13:15,963 --> 00:13:17,589
I didn't expect things
to change so suddenly.

331
00:13:18,090 --> 00:13:20,008
I still wanted to learn stuff from them.

332
00:13:20,425 --> 00:13:22,636
Even though you were a pro,
you were still a child.

333
00:13:22,719 --> 00:13:24,721
- But in Go, you were treated as an adult.
- Exactly.

334
00:13:24,805 --> 00:13:26,682
- In Go, I was already a professional.
- Right.

335
00:13:27,015 --> 00:13:28,892
Being a professional player
is really difficult.

336
00:13:29,977 --> 00:13:31,812
Everything was completely different.

337
00:13:32,271 --> 00:13:34,439
By 1996, when I was 14 years old,

338
00:13:34,815 --> 00:13:37,609
I realized how difficult it was
to be a professional Go player.

339
00:13:37,901 --> 00:13:39,069
It was harder than I thought.

340
00:13:39,361 --> 00:13:43,991
In fact, I didn't really achieve anything
until I was 16 years old.

341
00:13:44,241 --> 00:13:47,160
Then when did you start
making a name for yourself?

342
00:13:47,536 --> 00:13:51,123
In 1998, my father...

343
00:13:52,124 --> 00:13:54,710
became ill with cancer.

344
00:13:56,837 --> 00:14:00,382
And he passed away
on my birthday, March 2nd.

345
00:14:02,676 --> 00:14:06,346
He said, "I can't die on
my youngest son's birthday," but he did.

346
00:14:08,599 --> 00:14:11,852
The thing is,
not every professional player

347
00:14:11,935 --> 00:14:14,062
gets to leave a game record.

348
00:14:14,813 --> 00:14:18,483
You have to pass the preliminaries
and make it to the main event.

349
00:14:18,692 --> 00:14:19,693
I see.

350
00:14:19,776 --> 00:14:21,862
So at the time, I didn't have any records.

351
00:14:21,945 --> 00:14:23,197
None at all.

352
00:14:23,488 --> 00:14:26,325
And I felt really bad about that fact.

353
00:14:28,702 --> 00:14:32,623
I really wanted to show my father
my game records.

354
00:14:32,706 --> 00:14:33,624
Right.

355
00:14:33,707 --> 00:14:35,250
- Of course you wanted to show him.
- Yes.

356
00:14:35,334 --> 00:14:38,086
I regretted not being able to
show him anything.

357
00:14:38,670 --> 00:14:41,089
Before that, I was still a child...

358
00:14:41,173 --> 00:14:42,174
You were.

359
00:14:42,549 --> 00:14:44,551
So I didn't have the grit

360
00:14:44,635 --> 00:14:48,472
or the intense desire to succeed
as a professional player.

361
00:14:49,264 --> 00:14:53,143
But after my father's death,
I resolved to try harder

362
00:14:53,477 --> 00:14:55,562
to make it as a professional.

363
00:14:55,646 --> 00:14:58,148
I got my results a year later.

364
00:14:58,273 --> 00:15:00,150
By 1999, I became much better,

365
00:15:00,359 --> 00:15:02,110
and from 2000,

366
00:15:02,194 --> 00:15:05,030
I began to win more games
and leave records as well.

367
00:15:05,113 --> 00:15:06,240
HIS RECORDS CHANGED
2 YEARS AFTER HIS FATHER'S PASSING

368
00:15:06,323 --> 00:15:09,535
I can't presume to know
how your father felt,

369
00:15:09,785 --> 00:15:10,786
but...

370
00:15:11,370 --> 00:15:15,707
he must've realized
he didn't have much time left.

371
00:15:16,166 --> 00:15:18,168
- And that's so--
- To be honest,

372
00:15:18,252 --> 00:15:19,670
there's...

373
00:15:21,213 --> 00:15:22,673
something I regret.

374
00:15:25,133 --> 00:15:27,135
Once, I came to

375
00:15:27,803 --> 00:15:30,639
visit my parents in Bigeumdo,

376
00:15:30,722 --> 00:15:33,267
and then it was time to return to Seoul.

377
00:15:34,518 --> 00:15:37,312
I had to take a bus
to get to the ferry terminal,

378
00:15:38,438 --> 00:15:39,565
but before I got on the bus,

379
00:15:40,107 --> 00:15:43,944
my father took my hands
and started crying.

380
00:15:45,779 --> 00:15:50,117
Looking back on it now, I was so young.

381
00:15:51,201 --> 00:15:54,830
I told him I needed to catch my bus
and just went on my way.

382
00:15:55,289 --> 00:15:57,916
And that was the last
I ever saw of my father.

383
00:15:59,251 --> 00:16:00,627
Why did I do that?

384
00:16:01,879 --> 00:16:04,506
I could've just caught the next ferry.

385
00:16:09,970 --> 00:16:11,972
What was wrong with me?

386
00:16:12,055 --> 00:16:14,850
Why didn't I just...

387
00:16:17,311 --> 00:16:20,856
You must regret
that you let go of your father first.

388
00:16:21,481 --> 00:16:23,150
I think that was the first time

389
00:16:24,109 --> 00:16:27,237
I'd seen my father cry.

390
00:16:28,864 --> 00:16:32,075
I don't think my father
ever showed his tears

391
00:16:32,284 --> 00:16:33,911
to his children before that.

392
00:16:34,494 --> 00:16:36,955
And especially not to his youngest son.

393
00:16:38,248 --> 00:16:41,752
That was the first time I saw him crying.

394
00:16:42,961 --> 00:16:45,255
But at the time,
you were just a teenager, right?

395
00:16:45,839 --> 00:16:48,842
And you were working hard
and trying your best

396
00:16:48,926 --> 00:16:52,262
to make your father proud

397
00:16:52,346 --> 00:16:53,555
as his youngest son.

398
00:16:53,639 --> 00:16:57,518
I'm sure your father knew all that.

399
00:16:57,851 --> 00:16:59,228
I'm sure.

400
00:17:00,938 --> 00:17:03,065
MY FATHER CONSIDERED GO

401
00:17:03,148 --> 00:17:05,484
NOT JUST A GAME, BUT AN ART FORM

402
00:17:05,567 --> 00:17:07,903
HE SAID EVERY STONE HAD DIGNITY

403
00:17:07,986 --> 00:17:10,072
AND EVERY MOVE CAME WITH RESPONSIBILITY

404
00:17:10,155 --> 00:17:12,324
BECAUSE OF HIM,

405
00:17:12,407 --> 00:17:15,661
MAKING THE BEST POSSIBLE MOVE
BECAME MORE IMPORTANT TO ME

406
00:17:15,744 --> 00:17:17,746
THAN MAKING A WINNING MOVE

407
00:17:17,829 --> 00:17:20,165
I LEARNED THAT THE PROCESS WAS
MORE IMPORTANT THAN THE RESULTS,

408
00:17:20,249 --> 00:17:22,918
AND THAT THE WAY I PLAYED
WAS MORE IMPORTANT THAN VICTORY

409
00:17:23,001 --> 00:17:25,337
FROM <i>LEE SE-DOL, READING THE MOVES OF LIFE</i>

410
00:17:25,796 --> 00:17:29,216
But after overcoming that first hurdle,

411
00:17:29,299 --> 00:17:32,135
you became stronger,
like <i>"dol," </i>meaning "stone," in your name.

412
00:17:32,344 --> 00:17:34,763
LEE SE-DOL BECAME AS STRONG AS STONE
AFTER BECOMING A PROFESSIONAL

413
00:17:34,847 --> 00:17:37,140
- Just like your name.
- I guess that's true.

414
00:17:37,349 --> 00:17:39,977
You had so many legendary matches,

415
00:17:40,060 --> 00:17:43,772
including the 10-game match against Gu Li.

416
00:17:43,897 --> 00:17:46,191
Can you tell us about that match?

417
00:17:46,817 --> 00:17:50,445
Many people assume that the AlphaGo match

418
00:17:50,529 --> 00:17:52,447
must've been the biggest event

419
00:17:52,531 --> 00:17:54,116
- Right.
- in my career as a Go player,

420
00:17:54,783 --> 00:17:57,744
but to me personally,
that 10-game match felt much bigger.

421
00:17:58,495 --> 00:18:01,123
Some people might not know
what a "10-game match" is.

422
00:18:01,206 --> 00:18:03,375
Not every professional player

423
00:18:03,458 --> 00:18:05,085
- gets to do this, right?
- You're right.

424
00:18:05,169 --> 00:18:06,545
It's a special match.

425
00:18:06,628 --> 00:18:09,006
Only the best players can play this match

426
00:18:10,215 --> 00:18:11,425
to determine who's best of the best.

427
00:18:12,009 --> 00:18:13,427
- You play ten games?
- Yes.

428
00:18:13,510 --> 00:18:14,386
- One on one?
- Yes.

429
00:18:14,469 --> 00:18:16,054
THE ULTIMATE MATCH IN THE GAME OF GO

430
00:18:16,138 --> 00:18:17,764
THE 10-GAME MATCH

431
00:18:18,473 --> 00:18:19,349
OVER A YEAR,

432
00:18:19,433 --> 00:18:22,561
THEY PLAY 10 GAMES
TO DETERMINE THE WORLD CHAMPION

433
00:18:23,145 --> 00:18:25,814
BUT LOSING THIS MEANS
BEING FOREVER BRANDED A LOSER

434
00:18:25,898 --> 00:18:29,735
SO THERE HADN'T BEEN
AN OFFICIAL 10-GAME MATCH SINCE 1955

435
00:18:30,444 --> 00:18:33,197
AT LEAST NOT UNTIL 2014,

436
00:18:33,280 --> 00:18:36,533
WHEN CHINA SUGGESTED
THEY BATTLE FOR THE WORLD CHAMPIONSHIP

437
00:18:36,992 --> 00:18:38,035
A 10-GAME MATCH WAS PROPOSED

438
00:18:38,118 --> 00:18:41,288
TO LEE SE-DOL AND GU LI,
THE NO. 1 PLAYERS IN KOREA AND CHINA

439
00:18:41,747 --> 00:18:43,040
SO BEGAN A HISTORIC MATCH,

440
00:18:43,123 --> 00:18:45,459
THE FIRST 10-GAME MATCH IN 59 YEARS

441
00:18:45,542 --> 00:18:47,461
First of all, who is Gu Li?

442
00:18:47,544 --> 00:18:49,421
He was your greatest rival, wasn't he?

443
00:18:49,505 --> 00:18:50,923
- Yes, he was.
- Was he?

444
00:18:51,006 --> 00:18:53,634
- He was the biggest rival I ever had.
- Right.

445
00:18:53,967 --> 00:18:55,886
In my age group, he was the best player

446
00:18:56,512 --> 00:18:58,138
in Korea, China, and Japan combined.

447
00:18:58,472 --> 00:18:59,765
After me, of course.

448
00:18:59,848 --> 00:19:01,850
THE BEST PLAYER AFTER SE-DOL

449
00:19:01,934 --> 00:19:02,851
NOT BAD...

450
00:19:02,935 --> 00:19:05,437
<i>- I hope he's not watching.</i>
<i>- But the thing is...</i>

451
00:19:05,521 --> 00:19:07,814
I meant it as the greatest compliment.

452
00:19:10,275 --> 00:19:13,904
SE-DOL ONCE CALLED GU LI
"THE BIGGEST GIFT IN MY GO CAREER"

453
00:19:13,987 --> 00:19:16,031
The first time we played
against each other

454
00:19:16,240 --> 00:19:18,116
was when I was 17 or 18.

455
00:19:18,200 --> 00:19:20,536
It'd been a while since I turned pro.

456
00:19:20,619 --> 00:19:22,037
- I see.
- It has been a while.

457
00:19:22,120 --> 00:19:23,163
And of course,

458
00:19:23,747 --> 00:19:25,415
I taught him some stuff...

459
00:19:25,916 --> 00:19:27,334
- And encouraged him?
- Yes.

460
00:19:27,417 --> 00:19:29,628
"You've gotten better at this."

461
00:19:30,337 --> 00:19:32,130
- "Don't give up, all right?"
- Yes, exactly.

462
00:19:32,506 --> 00:19:33,882
And for

463
00:19:34,299 --> 00:19:35,467
maybe five years...

464
00:19:35,551 --> 00:19:38,637
No, more specifically, from 2005 to 2008,

465
00:19:39,137 --> 00:19:42,266
I guess I was the best Go player
in the world

466
00:19:42,349 --> 00:19:44,226
for those three or four years.

467
00:19:44,810 --> 00:19:46,687
It's embarrassing to say that, but still.

468
00:19:46,770 --> 00:19:49,356
Don't be. The records prove
you were the best.

469
00:19:49,439 --> 00:19:53,277
Then in 2009, I went against Gu Li
in the finals for the first time.

470
00:19:53,360 --> 00:19:54,278
Okay.

471
00:19:54,361 --> 00:19:56,113
It was the first time
we met in the finals,

472
00:19:56,488 --> 00:19:59,074
and I ended up losing 0-2.

473
00:19:59,908 --> 00:20:01,535
- In your first finals?
- Yes.

474
00:20:01,618 --> 00:20:04,955
From then, until around 2012,

475
00:20:05,038 --> 00:20:07,583
Gu Li and I won two matches each

476
00:20:07,666 --> 00:20:09,668
in those four years.

477
00:20:09,751 --> 00:20:11,920
I think the Chinese were annoyed about it,

478
00:20:12,004 --> 00:20:13,630
because the thing is,

479
00:20:13,714 --> 00:20:15,716
when I lose, I lose big.

480
00:20:15,799 --> 00:20:17,593
- You're totally defeated?
- Yes.

481
00:20:17,676 --> 00:20:19,219
But when I win, I barely win.

482
00:20:20,220 --> 00:20:22,472
THE BEST WAY TO ANNOY THE OTHER TEAM:
WIN BY 0.5 POINTS

483
00:20:22,556 --> 00:20:23,974
- That must be annoying.
- Yes.

484
00:20:24,057 --> 00:20:26,268
- But it's exhilarating.
- Definitely.

485
00:20:27,311 --> 00:20:29,855
I'd manage to turn a losing game around,

486
00:20:29,938 --> 00:20:31,190
but just barely.

487
00:20:31,648 --> 00:20:34,026
I'd win by the tiniest margin.

488
00:20:34,109 --> 00:20:35,194
Almost no difference at all.

489
00:20:35,277 --> 00:20:36,945
When I calculated the points,

490
00:20:37,029 --> 00:20:40,407
I realized I'd won by 4.5 points
over 5 games.

491
00:20:40,782 --> 00:20:43,577
Even though Gu Li would win
by a higher score,

492
00:20:43,702 --> 00:20:45,162
we technically both had
two wins each and a tie.

493
00:20:45,245 --> 00:20:46,872
- We were equal.
- Right.

494
00:20:47,497 --> 00:20:49,458
In the end,
you had the same number of victories.

495
00:20:49,541 --> 00:20:51,251
HE LOST GREATLY, BARELY WON,
AND ENDED UP TYING

496
00:20:51,335 --> 00:20:52,544
THAT'S WHAT THEY FOUND ANNOYING

497
00:20:52,794 --> 00:20:54,880
Seeing that, the Chinese must've thought

498
00:20:54,963 --> 00:20:57,758
that Gu Li was much better than me

499
00:20:57,841 --> 00:20:59,885
and that it was a coincidence
that we tied.

500
00:21:00,469 --> 00:21:02,471
So they suggested the 10-game match

501
00:21:02,554 --> 00:21:05,599
- to determine who the real winner was.
- I see.

502
00:21:05,682 --> 00:21:08,185
Gu Li and I discussed it a lot in 2013.

503
00:21:08,393 --> 00:21:09,978
- About whether you'd accept it or not?
- Yes.

504
00:21:10,062 --> 00:21:12,356
- We talked about it endlessly.
- Makes sense.

505
00:21:12,689 --> 00:21:16,109
Because the risks involved in losing
were too great.

506
00:21:17,361 --> 00:21:18,820
But in the end,

507
00:21:19,363 --> 00:21:20,906
we decided that, despite the risk,

508
00:21:20,989 --> 00:21:24,159
we couldn't pass up
on such a prestigious opportunity.

509
00:21:25,035 --> 00:21:25,953
So we did it.

510
00:21:27,412 --> 00:21:30,624
SO THE 10-GAME MATCH
BETWEEN LEE SE-DOL AND GU LI WAS HELD

511
00:21:30,707 --> 00:21:33,210
TO DETERMINE THE NO. 1 PLAYER IN THE WORLD

512
00:21:33,293 --> 00:21:34,503
6TH GAME, JULY 2014, IN LU'AN, CHINA

513
00:21:34,586 --> 00:21:35,838
7TH GAME, AUGUST 2014, IN LHASA, CHINA

514
00:21:35,921 --> 00:21:37,005
8TH GAME, SEPTEMBER 2014,
IN CHONGQING, CHINA

515
00:21:37,089 --> 00:21:38,382
THE BATTLE OF CHAMPIONS
FROM CHINA AND KOREA

516
00:21:38,465 --> 00:21:39,716
LEE SE-DOL AND GU LI DUEL
IN THE 10-GAME MATCH

517
00:21:39,800 --> 00:21:40,968
THE MATCH OF THE CENTURY

518
00:21:41,051 --> 00:21:42,302
THE 10-GAME MATCH
THAT WILL DETERMINE THEIR FATES BEGINS

519
00:21:42,386 --> 00:21:43,512
BORN IN 1983

520
00:21:43,595 --> 00:21:44,930
WENT PRO IN 1995

521
00:21:45,013 --> 00:21:46,473
NO. 1 IN THEIR COUNTRY

522
00:21:46,557 --> 00:21:49,393
NUMBER OF TITLES:
41 FOR LEE SE-DOL, 40 FOR GU LI

523
00:21:49,810 --> 00:21:55,274
SIMILAR BUT DIFFERENT
THE GREATEST RIVALRY IN GO HISTORY

524
00:21:55,357 --> 00:21:57,818
Originally, we meant to start in March

525
00:21:57,901 --> 00:22:00,028
and end the games by December.

526
00:22:00,404 --> 00:22:01,697
But it ended more quickly.

527
00:22:02,072 --> 00:22:03,073
I'm...

528
00:22:04,283 --> 00:22:05,534
sorry, Gu Li.

529
00:22:05,993 --> 00:22:08,745
THANKS TO SE-DOL'S CONSECUTIVE WINS,
ONLY 8 GAMES WERE HELD

530
00:22:09,454 --> 00:22:11,290
Fortunately, I managed to beat him 6-2.

531
00:22:11,957 --> 00:22:15,002
But the results
weren't that important to me.

532
00:22:15,377 --> 00:22:19,047
What was more important
was the honor of having participated

533
00:22:19,256 --> 00:22:20,841
- in a 10-game match.
- I see.

534
00:22:21,466 --> 00:22:23,260
Not only were you great rivals,

535
00:22:23,343 --> 00:22:25,095
but you must've been great friends too.

536
00:22:25,179 --> 00:22:27,139
We'd get together in our hotel rooms

537
00:22:27,347 --> 00:22:28,849
to talk and laugh.

538
00:22:28,932 --> 00:22:30,517
We'd say, "If we tie,

539
00:22:30,601 --> 00:22:32,519
we'll both get super rich."

540
00:22:32,686 --> 00:22:34,438
IN THAT CASE, THE PRIZE MONEY
WOULD BE DIVIDED IN HALF

541
00:22:34,521 --> 00:22:36,857
"Maybe it'll end up
being an 11-game match."

542
00:22:36,940 --> 00:22:39,443
THE PRIZE MONEY WAS 850 MILLION WON,
THE HIGHEST IN GO HISTORY

543
00:22:39,526 --> 00:22:40,903
- If you tie...
- Yes.

544
00:22:40,986 --> 00:22:45,616
AFTER LOSING THE 10-GAME MATCH,
GU LI WAS ASKED,

545
00:22:45,908 --> 00:22:48,911
"DO YOU RESENT LEE SE-DOL
FOR BEATING YOU?"

546
00:22:48,994 --> 00:22:53,081
HE SAID, "THE RESENTMENT WAS SHORT,
THE LOVE WAS GREATER"

547
00:22:55,667 --> 00:22:57,753
You had another legendary match

548
00:22:57,836 --> 00:22:59,213
against AlphaGo.

549
00:22:59,713 --> 00:23:02,591
You're the only human
who's ever won against an AI.

550
00:23:02,674 --> 00:23:05,677
THEY PLAYED 5 MATCHES IN 2016
<i>Lee Se-dol, the Go world champion,</i>

551
00:23:05,761 --> 00:23:08,597
<i>is playing against AlphaGo,</i>
<i>Google's AI computer program.</i>

552
00:23:08,680 --> 00:23:10,933
<i>The match begins this afternoon.</i>

553
00:23:11,016 --> 00:23:13,936
I've never been praised
for winning a single game before.

554
00:23:14,019 --> 00:23:16,396
THE ONLY PERSON
TO HAVE EVER WON AGAINST AN AI

555
00:23:16,480 --> 00:23:18,440
How did this match come to be?

556
00:23:20,025 --> 00:23:21,652
They first approached me

557
00:23:21,735 --> 00:23:24,112
after the 2015 MLily Cup finals,

558
00:23:24,196 --> 00:23:26,323
<i>where I lost to Ke Jie.</i>

559
00:23:26,907 --> 00:23:29,576
Normally, when a player loses
a big match like that,

560
00:23:30,035 --> 00:23:31,328
nobody contacts them for a while

561
00:23:31,537 --> 00:23:34,456
to give them some time
to recover and regroup.

562
00:23:34,581 --> 00:23:36,333
But I got a call right after the match,

563
00:23:36,416 --> 00:23:38,126
maybe on the same day.

564
00:23:38,210 --> 00:23:39,711
I was in China at the time.

565
00:23:39,795 --> 00:23:41,213
Who called you?

566
00:23:41,296 --> 00:23:43,006
- A junior player.
- I see.

567
00:23:43,674 --> 00:23:45,717
I answered the phone,

568
00:23:45,801 --> 00:23:49,054
and he asked me if I could
spare some time when I returned to Korea.

569
00:23:49,221 --> 00:23:51,807
So I met up with him the next day.

570
00:23:52,891 --> 00:23:55,727
First, he made me sign an NDA.

571
00:23:56,144 --> 00:23:57,604
At first, I thought this would be

572
00:23:57,771 --> 00:23:59,481
an interesting demonstration,
nothing more.

573
00:23:59,565 --> 00:24:01,900
Granted, a computer could already
beat a human in chess,

574
00:24:01,984 --> 00:24:05,737
so I thought that'd happen
to the game of Go sooner or later as well.

575
00:24:05,946 --> 00:24:09,658
But I didn't think it'd happen in 2016.

576
00:24:09,867 --> 00:24:11,827
- Weren't you worried at all?
- Well...

577
00:24:11,910 --> 00:24:12,828
Not at all.

578
00:24:13,036 --> 00:24:14,246
You didn't think you'd lose?

579
00:24:14,329 --> 00:24:16,915
That never even crossed my mind.

580
00:24:17,165 --> 00:24:20,878
I probably said, "I'm not so sure..."

581
00:24:21,378 --> 00:24:23,630
- "Not sure I'd lose," right?
- Yes.

582
00:24:24,464 --> 00:24:27,593
HIS STATEMENT BECAME VIRAL
That was what I thought back then.

583
00:24:28,218 --> 00:24:30,596
- I didn't expect to lose at all.
- I see.

584
00:24:30,679 --> 00:24:32,931
One day, an AI expert came to see me.

585
00:24:34,099 --> 00:24:35,350
He told me,

586
00:24:35,559 --> 00:24:38,228
"Getting an AI to a certain point
may be difficult,

587
00:24:38,312 --> 00:24:41,690
but once we get it there,
it'll evolve exponentially."

588
00:24:41,773 --> 00:24:42,816
I see.

589
00:24:43,275 --> 00:24:44,401
He was warning me

590
00:24:44,651 --> 00:24:47,112
to be prepared for anything.

591
00:24:48,030 --> 00:24:49,531
I asked him if he played Go,

592
00:24:50,073 --> 00:24:51,241
and he said no.

593
00:24:52,034 --> 00:24:54,494
So I thought,
"That's why you're saying that!"

594
00:24:54,578 --> 00:24:55,829
MOST EXPERTS AT THE TIME
AGREED WITH SE-DOL

595
00:24:55,913 --> 00:24:58,999
So I didn't heed his warning,

596
00:24:59,082 --> 00:25:00,918
- but--
- You just decided to forget it?

597
00:25:01,001 --> 00:25:02,711
Yes, immediately.

598
00:25:02,794 --> 00:25:03,921
It was as if I hadn't even heard him.

599
00:25:05,005 --> 00:25:08,592
Then there was an opening ceremony
the day before the match,

600
00:25:08,926 --> 00:25:10,552
in which they talked about

601
00:25:10,636 --> 00:25:13,514
how this technology
was going to benefit humanity

602
00:25:13,597 --> 00:25:16,391
no matter what the outcome
of the match might be.

603
00:25:16,475 --> 00:25:18,268
And I immediately thought,

604
00:25:18,352 --> 00:25:20,062
"Oh, they think I'll lose."

605
00:25:22,105 --> 00:25:24,650
It felt like they were
assuming my loss already.

606
00:25:25,108 --> 00:25:26,610
But how could they be so confident?

607
00:25:27,361 --> 00:25:28,862
For the first time,

608
00:25:29,279 --> 00:25:30,656
I thought something was off.

609
00:25:30,739 --> 00:25:33,575
I wondered,
"Is this just what Westerners are like?"

610
00:25:33,992 --> 00:25:36,370
Then finally, the match began.

611
00:25:37,246 --> 00:25:39,831
Well, the program was
better than I thought.

612
00:25:40,332 --> 00:25:43,377
That was my first impression.

613
00:25:43,460 --> 00:25:45,170
Then I felt a sense of alienation.

614
00:25:46,463 --> 00:25:49,383
Aja Huang was sitting in front of me
and placing the stones for AlphaGo.

615
00:25:49,466 --> 00:25:50,551
HE IS AN AMATEUR 6-DAN
AND A DEEPMIND TEAM MEMBER

616
00:25:50,634 --> 00:25:52,553
Normally, when we play a Go match,

617
00:25:52,636 --> 00:25:55,472
we're acutely aware of the energy
and the rhythm of our opponents

618
00:25:56,682 --> 00:25:58,350
as we play the game.

619
00:25:59,017 --> 00:26:02,187
But Mr. Huang was just doing
what AlphaGo told him to do,

620
00:26:02,437 --> 00:26:04,147
so he had no intentions of his own.

621
00:26:04,481 --> 00:26:06,483
So I couldn't feel anything

622
00:26:06,567 --> 00:26:08,277
<i>from my opponent.</i>

623
00:26:09,027 --> 00:26:11,572
<i>Experiencing that discrepancy firsthand</i>

624
00:26:11,655 --> 00:26:14,324
felt so strange and alienating.

625
00:26:15,033 --> 00:26:16,743
To be honest,
that hindered my performance.

626
00:26:17,953 --> 00:26:19,454
After I lost the first game,

627
00:26:19,538 --> 00:26:21,832
- I just told the interviewers
- Yes?

628
00:26:21,957 --> 00:26:24,251
that I'd do my best to win next time,

629
00:26:24,334 --> 00:26:26,837
but in my mind, I was thinking,

630
00:26:27,254 --> 00:26:29,131
"I'll definitely win next time!"

631
00:26:31,592 --> 00:26:33,427
I wasn't at my best, so...

632
00:26:35,679 --> 00:26:37,931
- You were just unsettled.
- Yes, exactly.

633
00:26:38,015 --> 00:26:39,600
I just needed some time to adjust.

634
00:26:39,683 --> 00:26:40,517
IT SEEMS HE ALSO LEARNT SOMETHING ELSE
FROM HIS FATHER

635
00:26:40,684 --> 00:26:43,437
And then the second game happened,

636
00:26:43,979 --> 00:26:45,272
and that was totally shocking.

637
00:26:46,398 --> 00:26:48,901
I couldn't even do anything.

638
00:26:48,984 --> 00:26:50,319
The AI beat you.

639
00:26:50,777 --> 00:26:52,946
But more than that,
what really unsettled me

640
00:26:53,572 --> 00:26:54,907
was that I didn't know why I'd lost.

641
00:26:55,991 --> 00:26:57,367
I couldn't determine the losing move.

642
00:26:57,451 --> 00:26:58,535
Oh dear.

643
00:26:58,952 --> 00:27:01,163
I needed to know where I went wrong.

644
00:27:01,246 --> 00:27:03,457
- So you could learn from it, right?
- Yes.

645
00:27:03,582 --> 00:27:06,293
Many people analyzed our second game,

646
00:27:06,460 --> 00:27:08,378
trying to figure out what happened

647
00:27:09,713 --> 00:27:10,881
and why I lost.

648
00:27:12,341 --> 00:27:15,469
But in the end,
no one could figure it out.

649
00:27:16,845 --> 00:27:19,806
The professional Go players
must've taken this very seriously.

650
00:27:19,890 --> 00:27:21,099
<i>It was shocking.</i>

651
00:27:21,683 --> 00:27:24,394
<i>- It was so...</i>
<i>- I imagine the mood was quite grim.</i>

652
00:27:24,478 --> 00:27:26,813
They couldn't even comment on the game

653
00:27:27,314 --> 00:27:28,565
or blame me for losing

654
00:27:28,649 --> 00:27:31,026
without understanding what was going on.

655
00:27:31,109 --> 00:27:32,528
Even if they wanted to,

656
00:27:33,153 --> 00:27:35,489
they didn't know what I'd done wrong.

657
00:27:35,572 --> 00:27:36,740
No one knew.

658
00:27:36,823 --> 00:27:38,450
I didn't know, either.

659
00:27:38,659 --> 00:27:40,661
Nor did the other players watching.

660
00:27:41,411 --> 00:27:43,580
That was the most shocking aspect.

661
00:27:44,498 --> 00:27:46,458
The third game was held the next day.

662
00:27:48,001 --> 00:27:49,586
There was no way I could've won.

663
00:27:50,337 --> 00:27:52,047
First, there wasn't enough data,

664
00:27:52,589 --> 00:27:54,049
and I was still in shock.

665
00:27:54,132 --> 00:27:56,009
<i>Running on 1,200 CPUs,</i>

666
00:27:56,093 --> 00:27:58,637
<i>the AI program AlphaGo is</i>
<i>beginning to prove its superiority.</i>

667
00:27:58,720 --> 00:28:01,390
<i>Lee Se-dol admitted his third defeat</i>
<i>after 176 moves.</i>

668
00:28:01,473 --> 00:28:03,267
HUMANITY'S THIRD DEFEAT AGAINST ALPHAGO

669
00:28:03,350 --> 00:28:05,477
A DISCOURAGING THIRD DEFEAT

670
00:28:05,561 --> 00:28:07,563
In your book,
you said you returned to your hotel

671
00:28:07,646 --> 00:28:08,689
after losing the match,

672
00:28:08,772 --> 00:28:10,858
but that you didn't remember anything.

673
00:28:10,941 --> 00:28:15,737
Yes, so I had to narrate that part
from my wife's point of view.

674
00:28:16,238 --> 00:28:18,532
MY HUSBAND CAME BACK TO THE ROOM

675
00:28:18,615 --> 00:28:21,410
AND STARTED PACING
AND MUTTERING TO HIMSELF

676
00:28:21,493 --> 00:28:24,454
HE KEPT TALKING TO HIMSELF
AS IF HE WAS POSSESSED BY SOMETHING

677
00:28:24,538 --> 00:28:26,456
UNTIL HIS FRIENDS TOOK HIM TO ANOTHER ROOM

678
00:28:26,540 --> 00:28:28,876
My wife doesn't know anything about Go.

679
00:28:29,084 --> 00:28:33,005
So when I started talking about it,
it must've sounded like gibberish to her.

680
00:28:33,338 --> 00:28:35,048
She didn't know
why I was telling her all that.

681
00:28:35,674 --> 00:28:39,553
But to me,
it helps to just say the words out loud.

682
00:28:39,678 --> 00:28:41,013
So I kept telling my wife

683
00:28:41,096 --> 00:28:44,474
what I should or shouldn't have done.

684
00:28:44,766 --> 00:28:47,060
And she was just like, "Okay..."

685
00:28:47,144 --> 00:28:48,312
NOT USED TO HER HUSBAND ACTING THIS WAY

686
00:28:48,395 --> 00:28:52,232
To her, it must've seemed like
I was out of my mind.

687
00:28:52,357 --> 00:28:54,610
- You weren't being your usual self.
- No.

688
00:28:54,818 --> 00:28:56,195
At least that's what I assume she felt.

689
00:28:56,862 --> 00:28:58,447
It was also our wedding anniversary.

690
00:28:59,031 --> 00:29:01,241
- Yes, I heard that.
- Our ten-year anniversary.

691
00:29:01,325 --> 00:29:04,161
So Google sent us a bottle of champagne
to congratulate us,

692
00:29:04,244 --> 00:29:06,079
which made me so mad.

693
00:29:06,914 --> 00:29:09,541
"I'm not in the mood
to celebrate anything!"

694
00:29:10,667 --> 00:29:12,503
I thought I'd get to enjoy it

695
00:29:12,586 --> 00:29:15,047
after defeating AlphaGo 3-0,

696
00:29:15,672 --> 00:29:17,674
but things didn't go as planned.

697
00:29:17,758 --> 00:29:19,301
They actually sent you champagne?

698
00:29:20,886 --> 00:29:21,970
This wasn't in the book.

699
00:29:22,054 --> 00:29:23,639
It was so maddening.

700
00:29:23,722 --> 00:29:24,765
STILL SEETHING

701
00:29:25,349 --> 00:29:27,100
What's interesting about this

702
00:29:27,684 --> 00:29:31,146
is that right after this,
you made that historic move

703
00:29:31,230 --> 00:29:32,940
that gave hope to humanity.

704
00:29:33,023 --> 00:29:35,275
It's what you would call
the "divine move."

705
00:29:35,359 --> 00:29:37,736
You're being too kind.

706
00:29:38,737 --> 00:29:42,282
<i>- Did it give up?</i>
<i>- AlphaGo admitted defeat.</i>

707
00:29:42,366 --> 00:29:45,327
THE MOMENT ALPHAGO ADMITTED DEFEAT

708
00:29:45,410 --> 00:29:48,705
<i>Lee Se-dol has finally figured out</i>
<i>how to beat AlphaGo.</i>

709
00:29:48,789 --> 00:29:52,668
<i>This proves that AlphaGo isn't perfect.</i>

710
00:29:52,751 --> 00:29:55,170
HUMANITY'S FIRST VICTORY AGAINST AI

711
00:29:55,295 --> 00:29:58,340
MOVE 78, ALSO KNOWN AS THE DIVINE MOVE

712
00:29:58,423 --> 00:30:01,802
In the third game, I launched an attack
at the very beginning,

713
00:30:01,885 --> 00:30:03,387
but that was a mistake.

714
00:30:03,470 --> 00:30:04,680
I shouldn't have done that.

715
00:30:04,763 --> 00:30:06,098
So I decided to make my move

716
00:30:06,473 --> 00:30:09,643
in the middle of the game
between the 50th and the 100th move.

717
00:30:09,726 --> 00:30:12,020
It wasn't some
groundbreaking concept, though.

718
00:30:12,104 --> 00:30:13,605
I couldn't attack near the end,

719
00:30:13,689 --> 00:30:15,357
because the more stones there are,

720
00:30:15,440 --> 00:30:18,735
the easier it is for an AI program
to strategize in the remaining spaces.

721
00:30:19,194 --> 00:30:21,238
But I couldn't do it
at the very beginning either,

722
00:30:21,905 --> 00:30:23,490
because there are too many possibilities.

723
00:30:23,949 --> 00:30:25,576
- Humans can't calculate all that.
- I see.

724
00:30:26,201 --> 00:30:30,330
That's why I had no choice
but to make a decisive move in the middle.

725
00:30:31,248 --> 00:30:33,625
Another thing I realized was that

726
00:30:33,917 --> 00:30:35,377
no standard strategy would help me.

727
00:30:36,170 --> 00:30:38,213
- I wouldn't beat an AI that way.
- Right.

728
00:30:39,006 --> 00:30:40,215
So what did you do?

729
00:30:40,299 --> 00:30:41,758
I caused a bug.

730
00:30:42,384 --> 00:30:46,346
One of the most impressive aspects
of AlphaGo's technology

731
00:30:46,430 --> 00:30:48,390
is its ability to eliminate options.

732
00:30:49,391 --> 00:30:53,145
- The programs that came before AlphaGo
- Yes?

733
00:30:53,228 --> 00:30:56,940
calculated every single move
that no human player would come up with,

734
00:30:57,024 --> 00:30:59,902
including the most absurd options.

735
00:30:59,985 --> 00:31:01,653
But AlphaGo can eliminate options.

736
00:31:01,987 --> 00:31:04,573
It doesn't consider options
that are determined unnecessary,

737
00:31:05,157 --> 00:31:06,283
which makes it efficient.

738
00:31:06,658 --> 00:31:08,869
But since this was in the early days,

739
00:31:09,286 --> 00:31:10,662
it sometimes eliminated

740
00:31:10,746 --> 00:31:13,290
- options that it shouldn't have.
- I see.

741
00:31:13,373 --> 00:31:15,000
That was its first weakness.

742
00:31:15,292 --> 00:31:18,045
The next was that it had a timer.

743
00:31:18,670 --> 00:31:20,380
- For every move,
- Yes?

744
00:31:20,464 --> 00:31:23,467
it had to take
exactly 50 seconds to think.

745
00:31:23,550 --> 00:31:27,095
The unexpectedness of my move
wouldn't really matter

746
00:31:27,262 --> 00:31:29,014
if it had a few minutes to think,

747
00:31:29,097 --> 00:31:30,724
but it had 50 seconds.

748
00:31:32,017 --> 00:31:35,812
That lack of time
caused a bug in its system.

749
00:31:36,939 --> 00:31:39,566
<i>At this point in the game,</i>
<i>things aren't going well for Lee Se-dol.</i>

750
00:31:39,650 --> 00:31:41,735
<i>But then he makes his 78th move</i>

751
00:31:41,818 --> 00:31:44,238
<i>and puts a white stone</i>
<i>between two black ones.</i>

752
00:31:44,696 --> 00:31:47,783
<i>After that, AlphaGo begins making</i>
<i>irrational, incomprehensible moves</i>

753
00:31:47,866 --> 00:31:49,952
<i>all across the game board.</i>

754
00:31:50,035 --> 00:31:52,120
This really looks like a computer error.

755
00:31:52,788 --> 00:31:55,374
<i>In the end, AlphaGo self-destructed.</i>

756
00:31:55,874 --> 00:31:58,585
A lot of people praised me for that move.

757
00:31:59,878 --> 00:32:01,964
But obviously,

758
00:32:02,047 --> 00:32:05,467
I have my own principles
concerning the game of Go, right?

759
00:32:05,551 --> 00:32:06,593
That's right.

760
00:32:07,636 --> 00:32:09,304
That move went against them directly.

761
00:32:12,641 --> 00:32:16,353
That was the first and the last time
I consciously made a move

762
00:32:16,687 --> 00:32:18,605
that I knew for a fact
wasn't the best move,

763
00:32:18,689 --> 00:32:20,357
or a fair one for that matter.

764
00:32:22,609 --> 00:32:24,361
- So it went against your principles.
- Yes.

765
00:32:25,696 --> 00:32:26,989
I mean...

766
00:32:27,114 --> 00:32:29,116
Of course I was up against the wall,

767
00:32:29,199 --> 00:32:31,451
but I wasn't the only one
feeling cornered.

768
00:32:31,785 --> 00:32:34,121
My wife and my child were with me,

769
00:32:34,204 --> 00:32:36,456
- I see.
- waiting for me in the hotel,

770
00:32:36,623 --> 00:32:39,459
and my colleagues and friends
were there too,

771
00:32:39,793 --> 00:32:42,212
as well as my countless supporters.

772
00:32:42,296 --> 00:32:45,215
If I thought I'd be the only one losing...

773
00:32:46,884 --> 00:32:48,635
I wouldn't have made that move.

774
00:32:49,761 --> 00:32:52,890
- You betrayed your principles for others.
- Yes.

775
00:32:53,390 --> 00:32:55,517
I've been taught that Go is

776
00:32:56,435 --> 00:32:58,145
- a form of art.
- I see.

777
00:32:58,562 --> 00:33:01,440
And from the artistic point of view,

778
00:33:02,107 --> 00:33:05,861
whether you win or lose
is just a by-product

779
00:33:05,944 --> 00:33:09,198
- of the process of art creation.
- Yes.

780
00:33:09,740 --> 00:33:10,991
So does it hurt you

781
00:33:11,074 --> 00:33:13,243
to make a move
that goes against your principles

782
00:33:13,368 --> 00:33:15,287
- just to win?
- Of course.

783
00:33:15,370 --> 00:33:17,748
It isn't just a small discomfort, either.

784
00:33:18,874 --> 00:33:21,293
If I were playing against a person,
I would never have made that move.

785
00:33:21,543 --> 00:33:23,378
It wouldn't have worked anyway.

786
00:33:24,338 --> 00:33:25,839
The irony is

787
00:33:26,173 --> 00:33:28,759
that the move that hurt you the most

788
00:33:28,842 --> 00:33:31,762
was the move that gave hope to humanity.

789
00:33:31,845 --> 00:33:34,515
I said something after the third game.

790
00:33:35,182 --> 00:33:38,644
"This was Lee Se-dol's defeat,
not humanity's."

791
00:33:38,727 --> 00:33:40,604
Wasn't that so cool?

792
00:33:42,981 --> 00:33:44,358
The timing was perfect.

793
00:33:44,441 --> 00:33:46,443
I should've held it in.

794
00:33:46,860 --> 00:33:48,237
HIS PRIDE IS BURSTING OUT LIKE A SNEEZE

795
00:33:48,320 --> 00:33:49,404
All right, then.

796
00:33:50,155 --> 00:33:52,449
After the match against AlphaGo,

797
00:33:53,033 --> 00:33:55,202
you enter a new phase of life.

798
00:33:56,370 --> 00:33:57,955
- You announce your retirement.
- Yes.

799
00:33:58,038 --> 00:33:59,873
Why did you do that?

800
00:33:59,957 --> 00:34:03,168
In 2017,
AlphaGo's master version came out.

801
00:34:03,252 --> 00:34:04,211
That's right.

802
00:34:04,503 --> 00:34:05,879
And I realized I'd never beat it.

803
00:34:06,296 --> 00:34:08,674
It makes incredible moves
that humans haven't thought of.

804
00:34:09,633 --> 00:34:10,843
I felt my limitations.

805
00:34:11,176 --> 00:34:14,221
It wasn't even about
whether I could beat it or not.

806
00:34:14,388 --> 00:34:16,223
- Did it change the world of Go?
- Absolutely.

807
00:34:16,306 --> 00:34:17,850
- Absolutely?
- Yes.

808
00:34:18,267 --> 00:34:19,643
Now, human players look at its moves

809
00:34:20,185 --> 00:34:21,395
and learn from them.

810
00:34:21,478 --> 00:34:24,940
We ask, "This move is so easy.
Why didn't we think of it before?"

811
00:34:25,566 --> 00:34:28,068
Of course, there are difficult moves too,

812
00:34:28,443 --> 00:34:29,987
but some are really easy.

813
00:34:30,571 --> 00:34:32,447
We were just too narrow-minded
to see them before.

814
00:34:32,739 --> 00:34:34,157
So that was shocking, too.

815
00:34:34,241 --> 00:34:36,785
And then AI Go programs
were installed everywhere,

816
00:34:37,494 --> 00:34:39,913
and professional players
began to study their moves

817
00:34:40,205 --> 00:34:42,583
from those AI programs.

818
00:34:42,666 --> 00:34:44,042
There are different types.

819
00:34:44,126 --> 00:34:45,836
AlphaGo Lee and AlphaGo Master

820
00:34:45,919 --> 00:34:47,629
learn game records of humans,

821
00:34:48,130 --> 00:34:50,799
but AlphaGo Zero doesn't even do that.

822
00:34:51,049 --> 00:34:52,426
It only learns the rules,

823
00:34:52,509 --> 00:34:55,137
then the AI learns to play all by itself.

824
00:34:56,096 --> 00:34:57,347
But the problem is,

825
00:34:57,806 --> 00:35:01,185
I don't understand what it's doing
because it didn't learn from humans.

826
00:35:03,061 --> 00:35:04,688
I don't know why it made its moves.

827
00:35:05,230 --> 00:35:06,773
- So you can't learn from it.
- Exactly.

828
00:35:06,857 --> 00:35:09,151
Sometimes, there are games
I can actually understand.

829
00:35:09,234 --> 00:35:10,819
"Oh, so this was the logic behind it."

830
00:35:10,903 --> 00:35:12,529
But sometimes,
I can't figure it out at all.

831
00:35:13,113 --> 00:35:14,698
You've been a Go player all your life.

832
00:35:15,032 --> 00:35:16,408
This is your game,

833
00:35:16,491 --> 00:35:19,494
but suddenly
it's not the game you know anymore.

834
00:35:20,787 --> 00:35:22,539
I don't really mind losing to AI

835
00:35:22,623 --> 00:35:24,708
since I can lose to humans, too.

836
00:35:24,791 --> 00:35:26,543
So I don't care about that.

837
00:35:27,753 --> 00:35:29,963
But I never expected
that I wouldn't even understand

838
00:35:30,214 --> 00:35:31,715
the game that was being played.

839
00:35:33,133 --> 00:35:35,719
That's a completely different matter.

840
00:35:37,846 --> 00:35:39,640
- Professor.
- Yes?

841
00:35:39,723 --> 00:35:41,058
Is that why you left?

842
00:35:41,433 --> 00:35:43,018
That was a big part of it.

843
00:35:45,604 --> 00:35:47,314
I started wondering...

844
00:35:48,857 --> 00:35:50,651
what's the point of playing Go?

845
00:35:52,236 --> 00:35:54,738
Of course, I won't speak
for the other Go players

846
00:35:54,821 --> 00:35:55,822
who are currently active,

847
00:35:56,281 --> 00:35:59,243
but for me,
the game lost a lot of its meaning.

848
00:35:59,701 --> 00:36:01,828
- That's my personal opinion.
- I see.

849
00:36:02,788 --> 00:36:05,082
That was a little...

850
00:36:06,291 --> 00:36:07,376
tough to bear.

851
00:36:07,459 --> 00:36:09,294
Not being able to understand the games

852
00:36:09,920 --> 00:36:11,213
was too much for me.

853
00:36:13,549 --> 00:36:16,051
People said, "Before you retire,

854
00:36:16,468 --> 00:36:18,846
we want you, Lee Se-dol,

855
00:36:19,304 --> 00:36:21,265
to impress us
one last time in this age of AI."

856
00:36:22,015 --> 00:36:24,309
A lot of people told me that.

857
00:36:24,393 --> 00:36:26,144
But I told them I was too exhausted.

858
00:36:26,645 --> 00:36:29,481
Playing Go in the age of AI
felt meaningless to me.

859
00:36:30,816 --> 00:36:33,151
I felt bad for disappointing them.

860
00:36:34,319 --> 00:36:36,780
I should've tried my best
to show them something

861
00:36:37,739 --> 00:36:39,366
despite everything,

862
00:36:39,908 --> 00:36:41,243
but I couldn't do that.

863
00:36:42,995 --> 00:36:44,538
Thank you for being honest with us

864
00:36:44,621 --> 00:36:46,206
and with your colleagues as well.

865
00:36:50,836 --> 00:36:55,340
WHAT DOES IT MEAN TO BE ALIVE
IN THIS MOMENT IN TIME?

866
00:36:55,424 --> 00:37:00,596
THIS MAY SOUND LIKE A QUESTION
THAT'S TOO GRAND OR VAGUE

867
00:37:00,679 --> 00:37:05,267
AND PERHAPS HUMANITY ISN'T AS GRAND
AS IT THINKS IT IS

868
00:37:05,350 --> 00:37:08,770
WE DON'T HAVE TO TRY TOO HARD
TO FIND MEANING IN EVERYTHING

869
00:37:08,854 --> 00:37:11,481
BEING TRUE TO THE LIFE YOU HAVE IS ENOUGH

870
00:37:11,565 --> 00:37:14,318
FROM <i>LEE SE-DOL, READING THE MOVES OF LIFE</i>

871
00:37:14,401 --> 00:37:16,904
- Chang Kang-myoung wrote a book
- Yes, I am aware.

872
00:37:16,987 --> 00:37:18,280
called <i>The Future that Arrived Early.</i>

873
00:37:18,363 --> 00:37:20,407
In his book,

874
00:37:20,490 --> 00:37:24,703
he describes you as
someone who has faced the future first.

875
00:37:24,786 --> 00:37:28,081
Do you feel that the role of humans
is slowly decreasing

876
00:37:28,165 --> 00:37:29,750
due to the development of AI?

877
00:37:30,292 --> 00:37:32,252
A lot of people are worried

878
00:37:32,753 --> 00:37:35,547
that we'll not just be replaced,
and our role will disappear entirely.

879
00:37:36,381 --> 00:37:38,550
But I don't think that's the case at all.

880
00:37:39,343 --> 00:37:40,802
That's not what I think.

881
00:37:40,886 --> 00:37:42,596
I think it's divided

882
00:37:42,930 --> 00:37:45,265
by things computers can do
and things humans can do.

883
00:37:46,016 --> 00:37:49,353
Computers are extremely powerful
in situations

884
00:37:49,436 --> 00:37:52,231
where there are
clear rules and limits, like Go.

885
00:37:52,314 --> 00:37:56,026
But what humans do

886
00:37:56,652 --> 00:37:59,780
is set standards
and the direction something should take,

887
00:37:59,863 --> 00:38:02,282
as well as add something
that makes it uniquely ours.

888
00:38:02,908 --> 00:38:05,118
I think that's the role of humans.

889
00:38:05,744 --> 00:38:08,747
Even if we live in a society where
there is artificial superintelligence,

890
00:38:09,623 --> 00:38:11,166
I don't think that'll affect our role.

891
00:38:12,042 --> 00:38:13,919
We have to live on in the age of AI.

892
00:38:14,002 --> 00:38:17,297
- Right.
- AI is continuing to evolve.

893
00:38:17,381 --> 00:38:18,340
But...

894
00:38:18,715 --> 00:38:20,551
I heard that you teach children

895
00:38:20,717 --> 00:38:22,845
that the game of Go is very important

896
00:38:22,928 --> 00:38:24,596
- to learn and practice.
- Okay, so...

897
00:38:24,680 --> 00:38:25,931
The game of Go

898
00:38:26,306 --> 00:38:28,934
is the only perfect abstract strategy game
in the world.

899
00:38:29,601 --> 00:38:31,812
I think it's important to learn
how to utilize AI technology.

900
00:38:31,895 --> 00:38:32,855
Right.

901
00:38:32,938 --> 00:38:35,774
And that takes human imagination.

902
00:38:35,858 --> 00:38:38,026
- You need to ask the right questions.
- Exactly.

903
00:38:38,110 --> 00:38:41,530
To do that, you need to practice
some abstract thinking.

904
00:38:42,364 --> 00:38:44,741
Another reason you recommend Go

905
00:38:44,825 --> 00:38:46,493
to our children and teenagers

906
00:38:46,577 --> 00:38:48,245
is because they can learn
valuable life lessons

907
00:38:48,328 --> 00:38:50,497
through experiencing failure, right?

908
00:38:50,581 --> 00:38:53,166
The game of Go
is only learned through failure.

909
00:38:53,250 --> 00:38:54,668
- Is that so?
- Yes.

910
00:38:55,169 --> 00:38:56,670
Losing is a given.

911
00:38:57,254 --> 00:39:00,215
You can also learn respect, consideration,
and responsibility.

912
00:39:00,299 --> 00:39:03,802
In this game, the most important thing

913
00:39:03,886 --> 00:39:05,721
is to respect and care for others

914
00:39:05,971 --> 00:39:08,223
and to take responsibility for your moves.

915
00:39:08,432 --> 00:39:09,641
- But Master Lee.
- Yes?

916
00:39:10,601 --> 00:39:11,977
Go is too difficult.

917
00:39:12,436 --> 00:39:14,271
That's both the pro and con of Go.

918
00:39:14,688 --> 00:39:16,315
I know that's an issue.

919
00:39:17,399 --> 00:39:18,650
It's great for you, but...

920
00:39:19,484 --> 00:39:21,862
- But it's...
- Isn't there any way to make it easier?

921
00:39:21,945 --> 00:39:25,240
That's why I developed a game based on Go.

922
00:39:25,324 --> 00:39:27,159
- I told you I design board games.
- Right.

923
00:39:27,242 --> 00:39:29,620
I believe I've simplified the rules a lot

924
00:39:29,703 --> 00:39:31,580
to make it much easier than Go.

925
00:39:31,830 --> 00:39:33,123
You designed a Go board game?

926
00:39:33,207 --> 00:39:35,042
- It's based on Go, yes.
- I see.

927
00:39:35,125 --> 00:39:36,752
Does it sell well?

928
00:39:37,169 --> 00:39:39,254
I can't say it does.

929
00:39:39,838 --> 00:39:41,507
YOU CAN BUY HIS WIZ STONE GAMES ON COUPANG

930
00:39:41,590 --> 00:39:42,925
Let me ask you a final question.

931
00:39:43,258 --> 00:39:44,593
This may be hard to answer,

932
00:39:45,636 --> 00:39:46,845
- but I'm looking forward to your answer.
- Okay.

933
00:39:46,929 --> 00:39:50,265
Reading back the records of your life,

934
00:39:50,807 --> 00:39:54,269
what do you consider your "divine move"?

935
00:39:56,063 --> 00:39:57,314
Getting married?

936
00:39:59,441 --> 00:40:01,485
- My wife and I are the same age.
- Okay.

937
00:40:01,985 --> 00:40:04,238
She's such a good person.

938
00:40:04,321 --> 00:40:05,489
Even though she doesn't know Go?

939
00:40:05,572 --> 00:40:07,658
That is kind of a shame.

940
00:40:07,741 --> 00:40:09,493
AS LONG AS HE DOESN'T SCARE HER
WITH HIS GO TALK AGAIN

941
00:40:09,576 --> 00:40:10,869
Yes, she's a great person.

942
00:40:11,328 --> 00:40:14,790
- Getting married was your "divine move."
- Yes, it was.

943
00:40:15,541 --> 00:40:16,792
A big round of applause.

944
00:40:18,293 --> 00:40:19,878
All right, now...

945
00:40:20,838 --> 00:40:23,215
You came for my book recommendation,
didn't you?

946
00:40:23,298 --> 00:40:24,216
- I did.
- Right.

947
00:40:24,299 --> 00:40:25,717
I forgot about that.

948
00:40:26,552 --> 00:40:27,553
Yes, I did.

949
00:40:27,636 --> 00:40:29,096
- Right.
- That's why I came.

950
00:40:29,638 --> 00:40:31,849
- We don't accept cash or credit cards.
- Okay.

951
00:40:31,932 --> 00:40:33,392
But that's all I have.

952
00:40:33,767 --> 00:40:36,603
THEY'RE PREPARED TO START AGAIN
FROM THE BEGINNING

953
00:40:38,105 --> 00:40:40,941
I thought long and hard

954
00:40:41,316 --> 00:40:44,736
about what my recommendation should be...

955
00:40:46,405 --> 00:40:47,447
and I finally got it.

956
00:40:48,907 --> 00:40:51,618
The book I'm recommending to you

957
00:40:51,952 --> 00:40:53,704
is <i>Guns, Germs, and Steel.</i>

958
00:40:55,247 --> 00:40:56,206
I see.

959
00:40:56,290 --> 00:40:58,000
Thank you. But...

960
00:40:59,126 --> 00:41:02,045
isn't this book too well-known?

961
00:41:04,131 --> 00:41:07,176
The author analyzes human civilizations

962
00:41:07,509 --> 00:41:10,929
in structural and environmental frames

963
00:41:11,138 --> 00:41:14,016
to investigate why some flourished
and some didn't.

964
00:41:14,099 --> 00:41:17,352
I know you like to read life
like it's a game board,

965
00:41:17,436 --> 00:41:18,395
but this book

966
00:41:18,937 --> 00:41:22,941
reads thousands of years of human history
like it's one giant game board.

967
00:41:23,192 --> 00:41:26,403
That's why I'm gifting you
Jared Diamond's <i>Guns, Germs, and Steel</i>.

968
00:41:26,486 --> 00:41:28,655
Thank you so much.

969
00:41:28,739 --> 00:41:30,866
I'll read it thoroughly.

970
00:41:31,700 --> 00:41:33,827
How did you like looking back on your life

971
00:41:33,911 --> 00:41:36,622
and reviewing its stories
like you'd review game records?

972
00:41:36,830 --> 00:41:39,708
It was such a precious time for me.

973
00:41:39,791 --> 00:41:42,127
I'm not just saying this to be nice.

974
00:41:42,544 --> 00:41:45,881
I certainly talked about these things
in other settings,

975
00:41:45,964 --> 00:41:48,884
such as an interview, for example.

976
00:41:49,593 --> 00:41:53,305
But talking to you
felt completely different, Hocrates.

977
00:41:53,805 --> 00:41:54,640
I mean it.

978
00:41:54,723 --> 00:41:57,684
Everyone has a different vibe
when you talk to them, right?

979
00:41:57,768 --> 00:41:58,894
Thank you. You're too kind.

980
00:41:58,977 --> 00:42:02,981
I think I'll cherish
the memory of the energy

981
00:42:03,065 --> 00:42:04,483
and the content of this conversation.

982
00:42:04,566 --> 00:42:05,859
Thank you so much.

983
00:42:05,943 --> 00:42:07,569
- The moment you step outside,
- Yes.

984
00:42:07,653 --> 00:42:10,197
this conversation will be
our cherished memory.

985
00:42:10,280 --> 00:42:12,282
And I know it'll be
my pride and joy forever.

986
00:42:12,366 --> 00:42:13,784
Thank you.

987
00:42:14,034 --> 00:42:15,911
This is a space
where people are read like books,

988
00:42:16,286 --> 00:42:20,040
located in the most beautiful neighborhood
in the world, Kangho-dong.

989
00:42:20,123 --> 00:42:22,584
Today, we heard
about Lee Se-dol's tasty life.

990
00:42:22,709 --> 00:42:24,294
What a great read!

991
00:42:24,795 --> 00:42:25,963
PARK SANG-YOUNG
Hello.

992
00:42:26,046 --> 00:42:29,800
I wrote the novel, <i>Love in the Big City,</i>
which got a film adaptation.

993
00:42:29,883 --> 00:42:31,134
You don't look like a writer.

994
00:42:31,218 --> 00:42:32,469
I have to make ends meet somehow.

995
00:42:32,553 --> 00:42:34,179
How do you think it got so popular?

996
00:42:34,263 --> 00:42:35,222
Maybe because I wrote it well?

997
00:42:36,348 --> 00:42:38,475
- My heyday hasn't come yet.
- Of course.

998
00:42:38,559 --> 00:42:40,811
This might be presumptuous of me,
but it feels like I'm talking to a mirror.

999
00:42:40,894 --> 00:42:42,479
TWO LOOKALIKES HAVE A CHAT
I think we have similar vibes.

1000
00:42:42,563 --> 00:42:44,523
WHO IS LEE SE-DOL?

1001
00:42:44,606 --> 00:42:48,777
DESPITE THE COLD GO STONES,
HE LEFT THE FINAL WINNING MOVE FOR HUMANS

1002
00:43:15,137 --> 00:43:17,139
Subtitle translation by Kim Ji-yeun
